+The dispatch driver and every in-repo component check the field first
+(see `_promote_successful_trials` in `eden_dispatch/driver.py`, which
+already filters by `trial.trial_commit_sha is not None`). Phase 7b's
+design preserves that convention: the field's presence is the
+integration signal.
+
+**External git readers.** A shell running `git log trial/*` directly
+has no access to the field and walks refs only. §3.4's "compensating
+deletes" mechanism is by construction incompatible with zero-width
+windows for such external readers — rollback writes a ref, then
+deletes it. The reference implementation accepts this trade:
+
+- On success (the common case), all three land and every reader
+  observes all three.
+- On rollback (the rare case), an external ref-walking reader MAY
+  observe the ref before the compensating delete; after stabilization
+  the ref is gone. A subsequent ref walk sees the rolled-back state.
+  §3.4 explicitly names compensating deletes as a permitted mechanism;
+  a permitted mechanism cannot simultaneously be a violation.
+
+Stronger guarantees — an instantaneous invariant surviving
+concurrent fs-level readers — would require either (a) a two-phase
+commit coupling the store's SQL transaction with git's ref write, or
+(b) an outbox where the ref write is derived from committed store
+state. Neither mechanism is required by §3.4; both trade against
+design simplicity and wire-protocol scope, and are more natural to
+introduce in Phase 8 when the cross-process wire is defined.
+
+**On compensating-delete failure** — if step 3 raises and
+`repo.delete_ref(...)` also raises, neither rollback succeeded. The
+integrator raises `AtomicityViolation` wrapping both causes. This is
+the irrecoverable state §3.4 names as requiring implementation-defined
+mitigation; the wrapped exception identifies exactly which `trial/*`
+ref is dangling so an operator can delete it manually.
